SIMPLE: unload
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Unload
<hw>Un*load"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <ety>[1st pref.
<ets>un-</ets> + <ets>load</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To take the
load from; to discharge of a load or cargo; to disburden; <as>as, to
<ex>unload</ex> a ship; to <ex>unload</ex> a beast</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, to relieve from anything onerous.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To discharge or remove, as a load or a burden;
<as>as, to <ex>unload</ex> the cargo of a vessel</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To draw the charge from; <as>as, to <ex>unload</ex>
a gun</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To sell in large quantities, as stock; to get rid
of.</def> <mark>[Brokers' Cant, U. S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Unload</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Unload
<hw>Un*load"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To perform the act of unloading
anything; <as>as, let <ex>unload</ex> now</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Unloader</ent>⟦br⟧
